Okay.

33
00:01:44.780 --> 00:01:48.300
Good. Thank you very much, Jing, for organizing this wonderful session.

34
00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:52.220
Thanks all of you for coming. So today I'll say a few words

35
00:01:52.280 --> 00:01:56.140
about our work over the last two decades, really, but especially the last four or

36
00:01:56.220 --> 00:01:59.700
five years in trying to use biomaterial models to

37
00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.460
study the process of glioblastoma invasion with steps towards

38
00:02:03.740 --> 00:02:07.450
identifying potentially therapeutically actionable targets and incorporate

39
00:02:07.500 --> 00:02:09.910
components of the stromal microenvironment.

40
00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:14.500
So as I mentioned, our lab is primarily interested in this invasive brain tumor,

41
00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:18.260
glioblastoma or GBM. And if you're not familiar with this, this is

42
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:21.340
not a tumor that you want to get diagnosed with.

43
00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:25.660
It's the most common primary intracranial tumor and has a really

44
00:02:25.960 --> 00:02:29.540
horrible clinical course in that median survival post-diagnosis

45
00:02:30.080 --> 00:02:32.820
is only about a year to a year and a half, and that's assuming you get very

46
00:02:32.880 --> 00:02:36.260
aggressive therapy, including surgical resection, radiation, and

47
00:02:36.460 --> 00:02:39.860
chemotherapy. This series of MRs in the upper left

48
00:02:39.980 --> 00:02:42.260
illustrates the clinical course of GBM.

49
00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:46.200
This is what a newly diagnosed GBM might look like, this mass lesion here in the

50
00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:49.840
right cerebral hemisphere. First-line treatment is surgical

51
00:02:49.940 --> 00:02:52.960
resection, if for no other reason than to palliate,

52
00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:57.820
typically coupled with radiation therapy and a chemotherapeutic

53
00:02:57.860 --> 00:03:01.820
called temozolomide. Unfortunately, patients will return more

54
00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:05.160
or less inevitably months later with recurrent tumor, as you can see with these

55
00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:08.120
hyperintense lesions near the surgical cavity.

56
00:03:08.489 --> 00:03:11.080
And then by 17 months, this is now a postmortem scan.

57
00:03:11.660 --> 00:03:15.340
So what this is intended to illustrate, in part, is that this is a disease of cell

58
00:03:15.380 --> 00:03:19.260
migration. Tumor cells have this uncommon ability to infiltrate brain

59
00:03:19.320 --> 00:03:22.960
tissue, and this both drives disease progression and also fuels

60
00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:26.840
chemoresistance, refractoriness to surgical

61
00:03:26.900 --> 00:03:30.420
resection, and so forth. So there's much interest in trying to understand

62
00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.180
how this invasion into the three-dimensional structure of

63
00:03:34.260 --> 00:03:37.540
brain contributes to GBM pathophysiology.

64
00:03:38.020 --> 00:03:42.000
There's also some evidence that invasion may contribute to chemoresistance at

65
00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:45.200
various levels, and this has particularly become an issue for anti-angiogenic

66
00:03:45.220 --> 00:03:49.060
therapy, which does a good job of reducing tumor mass but is

67
00:03:49.120 --> 00:03:52.880
often accompanied by this invasive resistance phenomenon, where choked off

68
00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:53.850
from

69
00:03:54.980 --> 00:03:58.460
generating their own blood supply, tumor cells will invade towards a host blood

70
00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:01.640
supply. And at the end of the day, there's very little survival benefit.

71
00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:03.880
Now, what makes this disease

72
00:04:04.820 --> 00:04:08.580
particularly challenging to model in vitro is that the architecture of the brain

73
00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:12.470
is not only very important but also varies quite a lot depending on what part of

74
00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:16.260
the tumor you're looking at. So classically, tumors are thought to invade

75
00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:20.019
locally through the peritumoral microenvironment or the brain parenchyma,

76
00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:23.500
which is very rich in a polysaccharide called hyaluronic acid.

77
00:04:24.030 --> 00:04:27.900
And then tumor cells will often home towards structures, the so-called

78
00:04:27.940 --> 00:04:31.460
structures of shear within the brain, including white matter tracts, as shown here,

79
00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:35.200
and blood vessels, and will sometimes migrate very rapidly along those

80
00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:35.940
structures.

81
00:04:37.040 --> 00:04:40.720
So I'm going to talk about the peritumoral portion of this today, our efforts to

82
00:04:40.740 --> 00:04:44.380
try to model this hyaluronic acid-rich portion of brain matrix.

83
00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.840
So, as I mentioned, the key player here in this portion of brain matrix is this

84
00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:52.380
sugar, hyaluronic acid, which not only organizes

85
00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:56.280
extracellular matrix proteins like the tenascins into a three-dimensional structure

86
00:04:56.780 --> 00:05:00.660
but also can directly engage receptors on the cell surface, most notably

87
00:05:00.700 --> 00:05:04.540
CD44. And as you may know, CD44 is more than just sort of a

88
00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:08.360
staple that holds cells to HA. It is itself also a fairly potent

89
00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:12.500
activator of oncogenic signaling, as well as a marker of tumor stem

90
00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:16.590
cells. So much of what we know about hyaluronic acid biology comes

91
00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:19.920
from our colleagues in the musculoskeletal field because this is also a very

92
00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:21.660
important component of cartilage.

93
00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:26.540
So you can purchase hyaluronic acid off the shelf, but if you put it into solution,

94
00:05:26.600 --> 00:05:29.920
you won't get a three-dimensional hydrogel that you can then implant cells into.

95
00:05:30.040 --> 00:05:31.400
You have to do a little bit of chemistry.

96
00:05:31.980 --> 00:05:35.440
And fortunately, there are some handles on the hyaluronic acid backbone that are

97
00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:39.160
amenable to that, including this hydroxyl group here, which we tend to focus

98
00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:43.080
on. So what we typically do is we'll convert the hydroxyl group into a

99
00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:46.620
methacrylate group, which is an acceptor for a type of chemistry called Michael

100
00:05:46.660 --> 00:05:50.050
addition chemistry, which proceeds fairly rapidly under physiologic conditions.

101
00:05:50.900 --> 00:05:54.550
And the story with this chemistry is that essentially anything with a thiol will

102
00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:57.590
rapidly form a covalent bond with these methacrylate groups.

103
00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:01.780
So we can do things like attach short adhesion peptides that ligate integrins as

104
00:06:01.820 --> 00:06:05.520
long as they contain cysteines, and we can also cross-link the HA into a

105
00:06:05.680 --> 00:06:09.160
3D gel using a di-cysteine molecule, something as simple as

106
00:06:09.220 --> 00:06:13.092
DTT.Or something as more complex or nuanced,

107
00:06:13.302 --> 00:06:17.112
such as a peptide that has two cysteines, where the peptide itself can be

108
00:06:17.152 --> 00:06:20.292
cleaved by cell-derived matrix metalloproteases.

109
00:06:20.332 --> 00:06:23.082
So we've been working with these materials for a number of years, deployed them as

110
00:06:23.172 --> 00:06:27.152
2D surfaces, 3D gels, as microgels for 3D printing, and here are some of

111
00:06:27.172 --> 00:06:31.152
our publications in the area. This has been a wonderful platform

112
00:06:31.192 --> 00:06:35.112
for us to study fundamental aspects of interactions between tumor cells and HA.

113
00:06:35.542 --> 00:06:37.312
And I won't go into this paper in great detail.

114
00:06:37.392 --> 00:06:41.332
This is the work of Kayla Wolf, a former graduate student in the lab, who's now

115
00:06:41.672 --> 00:06:44.532
a faculty member at Cornell in biomedical engineering.

116
00:06:44.552 --> 00:06:48.032
And long story short, she discovered a mechanism where tumor cells engage

117
00:06:48.212 --> 00:06:51.712
HA through structures called microtentacles, similar to what one finds on

118
00:06:51.912 --> 00:06:55.732
circulating tumor cells. And she was able to elucidate this molecular

119
00:06:55.832 --> 00:06:59.602
complex that provides a mechanism both for attachment to HA and

120
00:06:59.612 --> 00:07:00.672
transmission of forces.

121
00:07:02.272 --> 00:07:06.172
And this is one of several studies we've undertaken

122
00:07:06.232 --> 00:07:10.192
where we've done deep dives into understanding how tumor cells engage

123
00:07:10.332 --> 00:07:10.652
HA.

124
00:07:11.552 --> 00:07:14.732
And they've been wonderful for mechanistic discovery, but they do have a number of

125
00:07:14.771 --> 00:07:18.672
limitations. The first is these platforms tend to be fairly limited in

126
00:07:18.712 --> 00:07:22.512
scale. So great for things like spheroid invasion studies, where you have

127
00:07:22.532 --> 00:07:23.892
hundreds of thousands of cells

128
00:07:24.812 --> 00:07:27.232
and are perturbing one or a handful of candidates.

129
00:07:27.732 --> 00:07:31.672
But if one is trying to do things like omics analysis or screening where you need

130
00:07:31.712 --> 00:07:35.492
to have coverage, the cell numbers aren't really great enough to support that.

131
00:07:36.372 --> 00:07:39.922
Additionally, because of this inability to cast a wide net, data from

132
00:07:40.272 --> 00:07:43.872
these materials can be difficult to benchmark against patient data, where

133
00:07:44.652 --> 00:07:48.302
almost universally with GBM, every newly diagnosed patient or tumor is

134
00:07:48.332 --> 00:07:50.812
sequenced, increasingly with single-cell sequencing.

135
00:07:52.232 --> 00:07:55.722
I mentioned earlier that these tumors are quite heterogeneous,

136
00:07:55.792 --> 00:07:57.432
particularly with respect to invasion.

137
00:07:57.492 --> 00:08:01.232
So if we were to take one of these preparations, homogenize the whole thing, and

138
00:08:01.272 --> 00:08:04.912
take a measurement, we might lose information associated with the most invasive

139
00:08:05.012 --> 00:08:07.192
cells, which is where the targets are likely to be.

140
00:08:07.952 --> 00:08:11.532
So some years ago, we decided to retool our systems and ask if we might be able to

141
00:08:11.592 --> 00:08:15.552
develop a 3D HA-based invasion platform for comparative systems-level

142
00:08:15.612 --> 00:08:18.851
analysis of invasive versus non-invasive cells.

143
00:08:18.871 --> 00:08:22.692
And the goal here is to try to identify biomarkers of invasive cells, and more

144
00:08:22.732 --> 00:08:26.112
ambitiously, identify therapeutic targets that could be acted

145
00:08:26.152 --> 00:08:30.072
upon. So I'll tell you about the work of Erin Aikens, a former grad student

146
00:08:30.112 --> 00:08:34.092
in the lab, who deployed our HA matrices into a device format where

147
00:08:34.132 --> 00:08:37.812
we could essentially load millions of cells into very large channels

148
00:08:37.852 --> 00:08:41.793
embedded within HA and watch the tumor cells invade, literally over the

149
00:08:41.832 --> 00:08:43.332
course of a month to a month and a half.

150
00:08:44.112 --> 00:08:47.832
And so we can watch this whole invasion process occur under the microscope,

151
00:08:47.872 --> 00:08:51.572
the so-called tumor in a dish. But where this is really powerful is that we can

152
00:08:51.612 --> 00:08:54.732
physically dissect out different regions of the tumor and subject them to

153
00:08:54.772 --> 00:08:58.712
comparative analysis. And in particular, we look at the core of the region

154
00:08:59.132 --> 00:09:00.052
of the tumor shown here,

155
00:09:00.872 --> 00:09:02.492
and then the invasive rim shown here.

156
00:09:03.172 --> 00:09:06.932
And where this is really powerful is we can now directly compare these data against

157
00:09:07.112 --> 00:09:11.012
data from patients. And so this work has been done in collaboration with Manish

158
00:09:11.052 --> 00:09:14.812
Aghi, a neurosurgeon scientist at UCSF, who can do

159
00:09:14.852 --> 00:09:18.161
site-directed biopsies from patient GBMs in his operating

160
00:09:18.232 --> 00:09:21.752
room. So, I'm skipping over a lot of preliminaries here, but this is

161
00:09:21.792 --> 00:09:23.352
nanoString analysis of

162
00:09:24.572 --> 00:09:28.172
the invasive rim of a patient GBM now versus core GBM.

163
00:09:28.212 --> 00:09:32.162
And this is worked-up sequencing data from our devices, essentially showing

164
00:09:32.212 --> 00:09:35.862
invasive versus core. And we're under no illusion whatsoever that we can

165
00:09:35.872 --> 00:09:39.792
recapitulate all of the nuances of a patient tumor with this very simple in vitro

166
00:09:39.872 --> 00:09:43.712
system. But where we see matches in hits between patients and

167
00:09:43.872 --> 00:09:46.712
our data, these are fertile ground for us to pursue.

168
00:09:47.332 --> 00:09:50.362
So in looking for those matches, one of the first things we noticed was that

169
00:09:51.072 --> 00:09:54.721
transcripts associated with reactive oxygen species signaling were greatly

170
00:09:54.732 --> 00:09:58.432
enriched, both in our devices as well as in patient tumors.

171
00:09:58.532 --> 00:10:02.252
And this work has all been published now for a couple of years, so I won't get into

172
00:10:02.372 --> 00:10:05.592
the workup. But we elucidated what we think is a mechanism that

173
00:10:05.652 --> 00:10:09.612
invading tumor cells use to manage high loads of

174
00:10:09.632 --> 00:10:11.772
reactive oxygen species as they invade.

175
00:10:12.232 --> 00:10:15.802
And it involves enhancement of a pathway called the transsulfuration

176
00:10:15.872 --> 00:10:19.852
pathway, which is the cell's endogenous mechanism for synthesizing cysteine and

177
00:10:19.892 --> 00:10:23.432
glutathione. And if we target that, either pharmacologically or

178
00:10:23.472 --> 00:10:25.452
genetically, we can limit invasion.

179
00:10:26.751 --> 00:10:30.472
More recently, another aspect of the tumor microenvironment we've been trying

180
00:10:30.532 --> 00:10:33.952
to come to grips with in our model is the mechanics.

181
00:10:34.372 --> 00:10:38.332
So brain tissue, like many other soft tissues within

182
00:10:38.352 --> 00:10:40.392
the brain, are what we call viscoelastic.

183
00:10:40.812 --> 00:10:43.982
So they're capable of both relaxing stresses as well as storing them.

184
00:10:44.452 --> 00:10:47.902
And this has a number of implications, both for the bulk mechanics of brain tissue,

185
00:10:48.152 --> 00:10:52.052
which needs to be very resistant to mechanical trauma,

186
00:10:52.552 --> 00:10:55.952
but also to the sorts of stresses that cells feel as they migrate at the

187
00:10:56.272 --> 00:11:00.102
microscale. Because in a stress-relaxing material, when a cell generates

188
00:11:00.132 --> 00:11:03.252
force, that force will be dissipated to some degree over time.

189
00:11:03.772 --> 00:11:05.872
And so that needs to be accounted for in the materials.

190
00:11:06.492 --> 00:11:10.212
This is the work of Emily Carvalho, a former PhD student who's now doing a

191
00:11:10.252 --> 00:11:14.152
postdoc in New York City at the new Sinai RPI Center for Bioengineering Precision

192
00:11:14.232 --> 00:11:17.641
Medicine. This is a review that we wrote on this subject when we were first

193
00:11:17.692 --> 00:11:18.952
starting to think about this problem.

194
00:11:19.512 --> 00:11:23.342
So we became interested in asking how we might be able to incorporate viscoelastic

195
00:11:23.392 --> 00:11:27.012
materials into our models. And Emily made the

196
00:11:27.812 --> 00:11:31.452
recognition fairly early on that the brain offers a

197
00:11:31.512 --> 00:11:33.972
natural way to think about modeling mechanical properties.

198
00:11:34.532 --> 00:11:37.792
And in particular, normal brain tissue, as I mentioned, is very

199
00:11:37.832 --> 00:11:41.032
viscoelastic, so it does a tremendous job at relaxing applied

200
00:11:41.112 --> 00:11:45.082
stresses. And that's correlated with a

201
00:11:45.092 --> 00:11:48.432
particular distribution of hyaluronic acid molecular

202
00:11:48.652 --> 00:11:52.641
weights. So a normal brain matrix tends to have very, very high molecular weight

203
00:11:52.892 --> 00:11:53.172
HA.

204
00:11:54.112 --> 00:11:57.932
And to some extent, correlations have been developed between

205
00:11:57.972 --> 00:12:01.012
tumor progression and HA molecular weight distribution.

206
00:12:01.612 --> 00:12:05.412
And it's known that the HA in the vicinity of a tumor tends to be much

207
00:12:05.472 --> 00:12:08.572
lower molecular weight, sort of raising this idea that the tumor cells might be

208
00:12:08.632 --> 00:12:12.172
degrading the HA as they invade.So Emily

209
00:12:12.972 --> 00:12:16.872
developed a set of materials, both with low molecular weight HA and

210
00:12:16.932 --> 00:12:20.351
high molecular weight HA, and was able to develop

211
00:12:20.552 --> 00:12:24.452
viscoelastic versions of high molecular weight HA, essentially by

212
00:12:25.072 --> 00:12:28.632
making solutions of high molecular weight HA and very lightly cross-linking

213
00:12:28.652 --> 00:12:31.932
them using one of these matrix metalloprotease degradable

214
00:12:32.032 --> 00:12:35.192
peptides and attaching RGDs for integrin ligation.

215
00:12:35.762 --> 00:12:39.532
And the idea here is that applied stresses are stored to some degree by these

216
00:12:39.572 --> 00:12:43.172
crosslinks and dissipated by the fact that these are very flexible, floppy

217
00:12:43.272 --> 00:12:47.212
polymer chains that can rearrange and move around as the cell applies

218
00:12:47.292 --> 00:12:47.592
force.

219
00:12:48.552 --> 00:12:52.152
So she developed a family of these materials, and importantly, developed

220
00:12:52.292 --> 00:12:55.412
one that matched viscoelastic properties of brain tissue.

221
00:12:55.472 --> 00:12:59.172
So these are our own measurements in an instrument called a

222
00:12:59.192 --> 00:13:02.972
rheometer. So this formulation, H80, relaxes

223
00:13:03.172 --> 00:13:06.772
80% of the stress that's thrown at it over some defined period of time,

224
00:13:07.212 --> 00:13:10.532
and this matches very nicely the stress relaxation properties of brain tissue.

225
00:13:11.232 --> 00:13:15.112
So the first thing that Emily did was to implant spheroids into these

226
00:13:15.152 --> 00:13:18.912
materials and ask if the stress relaxation properties

227
00:13:18.972 --> 00:13:22.702
changed the way that they invade. And she found very strikingly that

228
00:13:22.972 --> 00:13:26.962
placing cells in these stress-relaxing materials, H80 versus L5, which is a

229
00:13:27.032 --> 00:13:30.492
very elastic material, greatly speeds invasion.

230
00:13:30.512 --> 00:13:34.502
And this is something that we see both in continuous cell culture models as

231
00:13:34.552 --> 00:13:38.092
well as in patient-derived GSEs. So we see faster invasion.

232
00:13:38.132 --> 00:13:41.242
We also see more cells escaping the spheroid as a function of time.

233
00:13:42.152 --> 00:13:45.852
So we started to play around with the tools that are

234
00:13:45.872 --> 00:13:49.582
available to us within these materials, in particular, including or

235
00:13:49.632 --> 00:13:53.292
excluding RGD peptides for integrin ligation, as well as making

236
00:13:53.352 --> 00:13:57.252
these crosslinks MMP degradable or not degradable.

237
00:13:57.272 --> 00:14:01.132
And the one thing that really seemed to control in this expedited

238
00:14:01.152 --> 00:14:02.972
invasion in the system was

239
00:14:03.952 --> 00:14:05.372
integrin ligation. So if we

240
00:14:06.672 --> 00:14:09.212
exclude the RGD peptides, these cells can no longer

241
00:14:10.832 --> 00:14:13.972
use integrins to engage the matrix. They no longer invade faster.

242
00:14:14.412 --> 00:14:18.172
But interestingly, if we make the crosslinker non-MMP degradable, they still

243
00:14:18.232 --> 00:14:21.892
invade just as fast. So this property seems to be independent of MMP

244
00:14:21.912 --> 00:14:23.612
degradation. I'll get back to that in a second.

245
00:14:24.752 --> 00:14:28.702
So to get a closer look at the dynamics of invasion, Emily returned to our device

246
00:14:28.772 --> 00:14:32.082
format, cultured cells in viscoelastic matrices in these

247
00:14:32.082 --> 00:14:35.772
devices, and asked if she could gain some insight into how they invade.

248
00:14:36.432 --> 00:14:38.732
And she noticed a couple of things that were very interesting.

249
00:14:38.912 --> 00:14:42.612
The first is that the first few cells out of the device tend to look very, very

250
00:14:42.652 --> 00:14:46.352
dendritic. And this is interesting in the abstract, but particularly

251
00:14:46.392 --> 00:14:49.352
notable in light of intravital imaging that's been done.

252
00:14:49.392 --> 00:14:52.462
And so this is the work of Frank Winkler, published in a number of incredible

253
00:14:52.552 --> 00:14:56.411
papers over the last decade or so, where he's able to watch

254
00:14:56.652 --> 00:14:59.712
tumor cells migrating in endogenous brain tissue.

255
00:15:00.132 --> 00:15:03.472
And the morphologies that we see are very similar to what we see from these, what

256
00:15:03.512 --> 00:15:04.372
we call leader cells.

257
00:15:05.212 --> 00:15:07.642
But only the leader cells really look like this.

258
00:15:07.672 --> 00:15:11.352
The cells that come out after the leader cells tend to follow almost single file

259
00:15:11.372 --> 00:15:13.472
linearly right behind the leader cells.

260
00:15:13.632 --> 00:15:16.772
So we describe this as a leader-follower-based invasion.

261
00:15:17.552 --> 00:15:21.332
And so it's tempting to think that the leader cells are sort of paving a

262
00:15:21.392 --> 00:15:25.032
way, creating a path within the matrix for the followers to follow.

263
00:15:25.572 --> 00:15:29.272
But we already showed that this effect is not dependent at all on matrix

264
00:15:29.312 --> 00:15:33.272
metalloprotease-based digestion, so how indeed might these leader cells be

265
00:15:33.292 --> 00:15:37.282
digesting the matrix? And so we hypothesized the leaders might be digesting

266
00:15:37.312 --> 00:15:40.972
the HA backbone itself to facilitate invasion using

267
00:15:41.092 --> 00:15:42.672
enzymes that break down HA.

268
00:15:43.672 --> 00:15:47.172
And so to test this, Emily did a number of studies where she

269
00:15:47.732 --> 00:15:50.082
used broad-spectrum hyaluronidase inhibitors.

270
00:15:50.112 --> 00:15:52.952
I'll show slides or images about that in a second.

271
00:15:53.452 --> 00:15:55.212
Also imaged some of the hyal

272
00:15:56.752 --> 00:16:00.692
isoforms, so hyaluronidase isoforms encoded within the human genome, and

273
00:16:00.712 --> 00:16:04.092
interestingly found that leader cells leave a little trail of

274
00:16:04.312 --> 00:16:07.952
HYAL2 right behind them as the followers follow.

275
00:16:07.992 --> 00:16:11.442
So it's sort of consistent with this idea that almost like a trail of breadcrumbs,

276
00:16:11.472 --> 00:16:15.292
except the breadcrumbs now are enzymes, are left behind digesting the HA and

277
00:16:15.332 --> 00:16:18.812
enabling these follower cells to migrate much more efficiently.

278
00:16:19.412 --> 00:16:23.272
And as I mentioned, if you throw broad-spectrum hyaluronidase inhibitors at the

279
00:16:23.292 --> 00:16:27.182
cells, you break this leader-follower dynamic, and essentially all

280
00:16:27.191 --> 00:16:30.992
cells are on their own. So every cell sort of becomes a leader, and as a result,

281
00:16:31.042 --> 00:16:32.852
migration is much slower and less efficient.

282
00:16:33.952 --> 00:16:37.792
You can really sort of see this HYAL trail idea in spheroid culture.

283
00:16:37.812 --> 00:16:41.512
So this is now confocal imaging of spheroids invading viscoelastic matrices.

284
00:16:42.032 --> 00:16:45.872
And you can see that leader cells leave almost like a comet tail

285
00:16:45.972 --> 00:16:47.992
of HYAL2 behind them as they invade.

286
00:16:48.452 --> 00:16:51.892
And you can sort of follow the path of followers as they move through the matrix,

287
00:16:51.932 --> 00:16:54.312
and they do so much more efficiently because a path has been cleared.

288
00:16:55.792 --> 00:16:59.752
Moreover, this HYAL-based digestion is associated with mechanical changes.

289
00:17:00.012 --> 00:17:03.432
So without getting into too much detail, we developed a way

290
00:17:03.492 --> 00:17:06.912
to dissect these devices so we could use atomic force

291
00:17:06.992 --> 00:17:10.672
microscopy to mechanically measure viscoelastic properties at

292
00:17:10.712 --> 00:17:14.093
different positions, essentially along the invasive front.

293
00:17:14.103 --> 00:17:17.312
And the data that we found was sort of consistent with this idea that I introduced

294
00:17:17.373 --> 00:17:20.952
earlier, that as tumor cells invade, they essentially chew up and

295
00:17:21.012 --> 00:17:24.412
fluidize the hyaluronic acid-based matrix, and we see both reductions in

296
00:17:24.452 --> 00:17:27.822
elasticity as well as increases in stress relaxation.

297
00:17:28.572 --> 00:17:32.532
And to some degree, that's borne out by a similar analysis that we did

298
00:17:32.632 --> 00:17:36.622
of mouse brain tumors. So taking cross-sections, doing

299
00:17:36.652 --> 00:17:40.492
similar sorts of analyses. The two

300
00:17:40.502 --> 00:17:42.012
parameters don't couple exactly

301
00:17:43.512 --> 00:17:45.752
the same between the materials and the tumor cells.

302
00:17:45.792 --> 00:17:49.432
But in very broad strokes, the idea is very much borne out.

303
00:17:50.712 --> 00:17:53.962
And if you're interested in atomic force microscopy and some of the technical

304
00:17:54.032 --> 00:17:56.872
details as to how to do these measurements, we published a paper just on the

305
00:17:56.932 --> 00:17:59.272
methodology at the end of

306
00:18:00.072 --> 00:18:00.992
2024.

307
00:18:01.932 --> 00:18:02.692
So this is sort of our

308
00:18:03.572 --> 00:18:07.192
model that we have in mind. The idea is that normal brain tissue is this

309
00:18:07.252 --> 00:18:10.872
very viscoelastic, high molecular weight-dominated HA

310
00:18:10.892 --> 00:18:14.192
matrix, and that as tumor cells make their way through the matrix, they

311
00:18:14.232 --> 00:18:18.092
secrete hyaluronidases, which essentially locally

312
00:18:18.112 --> 00:18:22.028
digest the HA matrix, thereby fluidizing it.And also creating a

313
00:18:22.068 --> 00:18:24.517
path for followers to follow through.

314
00:18:24.528 --> 00:18:27.528
And this is something that we typically don't see in these highly elastic, low

315
00:18:27.568 --> 00:18:31.488
molecular rate matrices. This does raise the question as

316
00:18:31.528 --> 00:18:35.088
to why viscoelastic matrices produce this behavior and purely

317
00:18:35.108 --> 00:18:38.838
elastic matrices don't. Our leading hypothesis, that this has something to do with

318
00:18:38.848 --> 00:18:42.608
the flexibility of the HA chains and their susceptibility to hyaluronidase

319
00:18:42.628 --> 00:18:43.768
digestion, but we haven't

320
00:18:44.688 --> 00:18:46.688
completely proven that just yet.

321
00:18:47.888 --> 00:18:51.548
And so this work was described in this paper that came out about a year and a half

322
00:18:51.588 --> 00:18:55.468
ago in "Advanced Materials," sort of describing both the material systems, the

323
00:18:55.548 --> 00:18:57.848
imaging, the cell biology, and the mechanistic studies.

324
00:18:59.088 --> 00:19:02.708
I'll just end by pointing you to some companion studies that our lab has

325
00:19:02.728 --> 00:19:05.958
published that I won't have time to talk about, but are very much in the same

326
00:19:06.008 --> 00:19:09.628
space. One question we've been very interested in is, how do

327
00:19:10.568 --> 00:19:13.868
cells remodel the matrices that we put them in to facilitate invasion?

328
00:19:14.428 --> 00:19:17.968
And so Jungua Cha, former post-doc in the lab, did shotgun

329
00:19:18.048 --> 00:19:21.868
proteomics on tumor cells as they were invading HA, just to ask

330
00:19:21.948 --> 00:19:25.238
what sorts of matrix proteins cells deposited, and

331
00:19:25.448 --> 00:19:29.368
discovered that this kind of unusual form of collagen, collagen

332
00:19:29.468 --> 00:19:33.188
VI, which is one of the microfibrillar collagens, is very heavily deposited

333
00:19:33.408 --> 00:19:37.348
into the matrix prior to invasion, and it seems to play a role in organizing other

334
00:19:37.388 --> 00:19:38.248
collagens to

335
00:19:39.728 --> 00:19:43.578
speed the process of invasion. Some other work that Erin Aikens

336
00:19:43.628 --> 00:19:47.308
did when she was a PhD student in the group was start to look at the paracrine

337
00:19:47.348 --> 00:19:49.368
effects of tumor-associated macrophages.

338
00:19:49.988 --> 00:19:52.768
And so in this paper, she discovered that

339
00:19:53.668 --> 00:19:57.568
tumor-associated macrophages secrete a number of matricellular factors that help

340
00:19:57.588 --> 00:20:01.468
to drive tumor invasion, including Biglycan H3, also

341
00:20:01.488 --> 00:20:01.868
known as

342
00:20:02.108 --> 00:20:06.108
TGF-beta-induced

343
00:20:06.308 --> 00:20:06.728
protein.

344
00:20:08.108 --> 00:20:11.988
We have also started to look at more broadly

345
00:20:12.068 --> 00:20:14.348
the role of paracrine factors in driving invasion.

346
00:20:14.448 --> 00:20:18.368
So Kwasi Amofa, a former graduate student in the lab, looked at effects

347
00:20:18.428 --> 00:20:22.258
of TGF-beta-induced invasion. And then Dana Wilkins, a

348
00:20:22.348 --> 00:20:26.048
current graduate student in the lab, in a first step towards studying

349
00:20:27.228 --> 00:20:31.227
neuroglioma crosstalk within the system, showed that even tumor

350
00:20:31.287 --> 00:20:34.928
cell-secreted glutamate is capable of driving invasion within these

351
00:20:34.968 --> 00:20:38.528
systems. And so we're just at the beginning of starting to use this system to more

352
00:20:38.628 --> 00:20:41.788
broadly incorporate components of the stromal compartment.

353
00:20:42.888 --> 00:20:45.768
So I'll stop there. I'd like to thank the folks that did the work.

354
00:20:45.828 --> 00:20:48.568
This is my lab in front of our building at UC Berkeley.

355
00:20:49.297 --> 00:20:53.108
The work I told you about, a lot of it has been done in collaboration with Manish

356
00:20:53.188 --> 00:20:55.428
Ahmi, neurosurgeon scientist at UCSF.

357
00:20:56.168 --> 00:20:59.528
We're starting to work more with Kenny Yu at Sloan Kettering on tumor-associated

358
00:20:59.608 --> 00:21:03.008
macrophages, and some collaborators involved with other work.

359
00:21:03.108 --> 00:21:06.708
This is the current membership of the lab. These are our funding sources.

360
00:21:07.148 --> 00:21:09.428
Thank you very much for your attention. Happy to take any questions.

361
00:21:18.148 --> 00:21:20.948
Hi, Cathy O'Connor from the University of Kentucky.

362
00:21:21.688 --> 00:21:25.648
Wonderful talk. I was wondering if you had considered the idea that

363
00:21:25.688 --> 00:21:28.928
your hyaluronidases might actually be secreted into

364
00:21:29.088 --> 00:21:32.848
microsomes. The patterning behind your leader

365
00:21:32.948 --> 00:21:36.848
cells are very much in line with the patterning you'd see in

366
00:21:36.908 --> 00:21:37.628
microsomes.

367
00:21:38.688 --> 00:21:42.577
Yes, we have. So, I didn't get into the data at this

368
00:21:43.268 --> 00:21:46.708
level of granularity, but it's not secreted as sort of a

369
00:21:46.748 --> 00:21:49.908
continuous line. They do seem to be punctate behind the leader cells.

370
00:21:50.478 --> 00:21:53.768
But I think we speculated in the discussion of that paper that those might be

371
00:21:53.868 --> 00:21:54.668
exosomal, but

372
00:21:55.488 --> 00:21:59.328
didn't feel comfortable enough to commit to that because we didn't do the

373
00:21:59.368 --> 00:22:03.188
usual due diligence you would do. But if you ask me to guess, I'd say that's the

374
00:22:03.708 --> 00:22:04.128
mechanism.

375
00:22:04.468 --> 00:22:05.308
Yeah, there's some nice

376
00:22:07.008 --> 00:22:10.528
staining mechanisms for microsomes if you're interested.

377
00:22:10.918 --> 00:22:12.328
I have one other quick question.

378
00:22:13.288 --> 00:22:16.748
My lab studies integrin alpha 6 beta 4, which is particularly high in

379
00:22:16.808 --> 00:22:20.748
gliomas and glioblastomas. I was wondering, because you're working

380
00:22:20.788 --> 00:22:24.368
with RGD peptides, which have nothing to do with laminin binding

381
00:22:24.408 --> 00:22:28.168
integrins, have you considered looking at laminins and their

382
00:22:28.248 --> 00:22:30.588
role in laminin binding integrins?

383
00:22:30.828 --> 00:22:33.748
Oh, yeah. Absolutely. So, my

384
00:22:34.588 --> 00:22:38.468
gestalt read is that the laminin mimetic peptides are not quite so

385
00:22:38.508 --> 00:22:41.737
laminin mimetic relative to the fibronectin, vitronectin ones.

386
00:22:42.268 --> 00:22:46.088
So, ICVAV and IGSR and so forth.

387
00:22:46.168 --> 00:22:48.388
So, we've tried to do that but haven't

388
00:22:48.428 --> 00:22:52.358
gotten as robust integrin mimetic

389
00:22:52.428 --> 00:22:54.078
adhesion as we get with the RGDs.

390
00:22:55.068 --> 00:22:58.888
I will defend RGD a little bit in the sense that there are some HA-associated

391
00:22:58.908 --> 00:23:02.648
proteins that do have RGD sequences, and this factor that we

392
00:23:02.888 --> 00:23:06.868
showed TAM secrete that drive invasion, Biglycan H3, has

393
00:23:06.908 --> 00:23:10.888
an RGD domain in it. And we've taken that RGD domain, stapled it onto

394
00:23:10.928 --> 00:23:13.468
our matrices, and it seemed to support adhesion and migration.

395
00:23:13.548 --> 00:23:16.348
But I agree with you. I think it would be good to

396
00:23:17.308 --> 00:23:17.968
be more broad.

397
00:23:18.488 --> 00:23:22.148
Yeah, it would be interesting to see if your laminins are actually secreted into

398
00:23:22.188 --> 00:23:23.328
your hydrogels, because

399
00:23:24.368 --> 00:23:27.828
we find that the integrin can actually regulate the expression of its own

400
00:23:27.868 --> 00:23:28.408
laminins.

401
00:23:28.708 --> 00:23:28.888
Yeah.

402
00:23:29.548 --> 00:23:33.368
Which is weird for an integrin to be able to do, but it may not need to be

403
00:23:33.428 --> 00:23:36.148
added as the cells can make them themselves, so.

404
00:23:36.208 --> 00:23:39.688
Yeah, now that you mention it, we're probably sitting on that data now.

405
00:23:39.728 --> 00:23:42.628
The proteomics that we did would, to some extent, have the answer.

406
00:23:42.788 --> 00:23:44.328
So, we will take a look.

407
00:23:45.928 --> 00:23:46.208
Thank you.

408
00:23:47.228 --> 00:23:50.868
Hi. Great talk. I had a question. So

409
00:23:51.248 --> 00:23:53.328
in one of your data slides, you showed that

410
00:23:55.868 --> 00:23:58.388
one leader cell kind of bifurcates it, right?

411
00:23:59.068 --> 00:24:02.048
So I just had a couple questions. One, do you see all of your leader cells

412
00:24:02.068 --> 00:24:04.208
bifurcating? And two, why?

413
00:24:04.458 --> 00:24:04.658
Hmm.

414
00:24:05.908 --> 00:24:08.628
Yeah, I don't know-- It's a very interesting pickup.

415
00:24:08.708 --> 00:24:12.528
I don't know that we see every one strictly bifurcate like

416
00:24:12.568 --> 00:24:16.548
that. I typically describe it as more of a dendritic type of morphology where there

417
00:24:16.608 --> 00:24:16.978
are many

418
00:24:18.428 --> 00:24:21.928
protrusions that are generated at the front of the cell, but with some

419
00:24:21.988 --> 00:24:25.028
hierarchy, right? There's maybe a sort of mother protrusion and daughter

420
00:24:25.088 --> 00:24:28.348
protrusions, but I don't know that it's always two or predominantly two.

421
00:24:28.848 --> 00:24:29.588
Okay. Thank you.

422
00:24:32.698 --> 00:24:35.298
Lovely talk. Thank you. Two questions.

423
00:24:35.778 --> 00:24:35.878
So

424
00:24:36.818 --> 00:24:40.758
thinking about the leader cells, is it always the

425
00:24:40.838 --> 00:24:44.558
same cell that become the leader cell, or is that a somewhat stochastic

426
00:24:44.578 --> 00:24:48.378
event that if you repeated this experiment 100 times, it will be 100

427
00:24:48.418 --> 00:24:49.818
different cells that became leader cells?

428
00:24:50.298 --> 00:24:51.958
And do you know what induces that sort of thing?

429
00:24:52.098 --> 00:24:54.598
Yeah, that's a really good question. Thanks for asking that.

430
00:24:54.678 --> 00:24:56.978
So the one experiment we have done is we've,

431
00:24:57.918 --> 00:25:01.598
after harvesting the invasive fraction, taken those

432
00:25:01.638 --> 00:25:04.518
cells, put them back into devices, done the same thing with the core.

433
00:25:05.118 --> 00:25:09.007
And the simple interpretation seems to be that

434
00:25:09.038 --> 00:25:11.178
every scenario is capable of generating leaders.

435
00:25:11.198 --> 00:25:12.558
So it's not some permanent

436
00:25:13.538 --> 00:25:15.918
modification that's made that confers that property.

437
00:25:17.018 --> 00:25:20.548
I will point you, though to-- We haven't explored this all that much, but a

438
00:25:20.578 --> 00:25:24.298
colleague, who is now at Rice, Cindy Reinhart-King, who works in breast cancer, has

439
00:25:24.358 --> 00:25:26.518
found similar sorts of mechanisms there.

440
00:25:26.578 --> 00:25:30.198
And she's elucidated these really elegant mechanisms where leader cells need a lot

441
00:25:30.238 --> 00:25:33.478
of energy to become leaders. They eventually run out of energy, so they exhaust

442
00:25:33.518 --> 00:25:37.378
their ATP stores, and then followers come up and become leaders while

443
00:25:37.998 --> 00:25:40.298
the previous leaders are resting and catching up.

444
00:25:40.378 --> 00:25:40.438
So-

445
00:25:41.658 --> 00:25:41.748
Okay

446
00:25:41.778 --> 00:25:44.498
... maybe there's something like that happening here, but I'd encourage you to take

447
00:25:44.538 --> 00:25:46.338
a look at that work because it's very impressive.

448
00:25:46.398 --> 00:25:47.018
Yeah. Thank you.

449
00:25:49.598 --> 00:25:50.038
Oh, yes.

450
00:25:50.158 --> 00:25:50.168
Hi.

451
00:25:50.198 --> 00:25:50.358
Yes.

452
00:25:50.798 --> 00:25:54.398
My name is Zoe. I'm a student at Heidelberg University and at Harvard

453
00:25:54.458 --> 00:25:56.998
University, and I have a question about the tumor microenvironment.

454
00:25:58.198 --> 00:26:02.098
Have you done any co-culturing with immune cells with your model, and how that

455
00:26:02.158 --> 00:26:05.378
would impact the layering, for example?

456
00:26:06.098 --> 00:26:07.618
Yes. Yes, we have. So that's

457
00:26:08.578 --> 00:26:11.578
easier said than done. I think anyone that's done co-culture can

458
00:26:12.338 --> 00:26:12.698
attest.

459
00:26:13.678 --> 00:26:17.638
We've done one or two at a time, so tumor-associated macrophages,

460
00:26:17.678 --> 00:26:18.738
endothelial cells.

461
00:26:20.218 --> 00:26:23.798
So the first thing with the

462
00:26:23.818 --> 00:26:27.078
tumor-associated macrophages we did was to actually do a co-culture, saw greater

463
00:26:27.138 --> 00:26:31.018
invasion in that setting. And then to get some insight into whether

464
00:26:31.418 --> 00:26:34.748
they actually need to be associated or whether it might be secreted factors, we did

465
00:26:34.778 --> 00:26:36.018
the conditioned media experiment.

466
00:26:36.458 --> 00:26:39.968
Conditioned media drove invasion just fine, so we stopped doing the co-cultures at

467
00:26:39.998 --> 00:26:42.798
that point and just focused on the conditioned media.

468
00:26:42.858 --> 00:26:46.258
But won't always be able to get away with that, especially for endothelial cells,

469
00:26:46.298 --> 00:26:48.118
where cells do actually migrate along vessels.

470
00:26:48.678 --> 00:26:51.978
So we've invested some time in trying to get that sort of system set up.

471
00:26:52.798 --> 00:26:56.578
And then, sorry, I have a second question, is are you working just with spheroids,

472
00:26:56.618 --> 00:27:00.358
or are you also working with patient-derived tissue material directly?

473
00:27:01.278 --> 00:27:01.918
Yeah. So

474
00:27:03.438 --> 00:27:06.308
that's been technically challenging to work with material that comes right out of

475
00:27:06.338 --> 00:27:08.678
